// Man page for iwlist
manIwlist="IWLIST(8)                        X Shell Manual                        IWLIST(8)

<b>NAME</b>
    iwlist - WiFi network interaction and cracking framework
<b>SYNOPSIS</b>
    <b>iwlist -l</b>
    <b>iwlist -d</b> INDEX
    <b>iwlist -b</b> INDEX
    <b>iwlist -c</b> BSSID ESSID PASSWORD
    <b>iwlist -u</b> INDEX|ESSID|BSSID|NICK
    <b>iwlist -n</b> INDEX|ESSID|BSSID|NICK [NICKNAME]
    <b>iwlist</b> <b>edit</b>|<b>-e</b> [INDEX|ESSID|BSSID|NICK] [FIELD] [VALUE]
    <b>iwlist -k</b> INDEX [ACKS]
    <b>iwlist crackall</b> [--all]
    <b>iwlist creds</b>
    <b>iwlist hop</b> [init [--all]|list|burn|revive] [-t SECONDS]
    <b>iwlist burn</b> [INDEX|ESSID|BSSID|NICK]
<b>DESCRIPTION</b>
    iwlist framework for interacting with wireless networks. Provides tools
    for listing available networks, connecting to access points, cracking
    network passwords using dictionary or brute force attacks, and launching
    deauthentication attacks. Use <b>iwlist -l</b> to display all available
    wireless networks in range before performing attacks or connections.
    Saved credentials live in the session data folder as <b>wifi_creds</b>
    (format: BSSID|ESSID|PASSWORD|flag|signal|nick). The <b>hop</b>
    subcommand bounces between clean saved networks.
<b>OPTIONS</b>
    <b>-l</b> - List Networks
      Display all available WiFi networks in range.
      Shows BSSID, ESSID, signal strength, and security.

    <b>-d INDEX</b> - Dictionary Attack
      Launch dictionary-based password attack on network.
      Uses wordlist to attempt password cracking.

    <b>-b INDEX</b> - Brute Force Attack
      Launch brute force password attack on network.
      Systematically tries all possible combinations.

    <b>-c BSSID ESSID PASSWORD</b> - Connect
      Connect to specified WiFi network with credentials.
      Requires BSSID, ESSID, and password.

    <b>-u INDEX|ESSID|BSSID|NICK</b> - Use Saved Credential
      Connect using an entry from <b>wifi_creds</b>.
      Accepts list index, ESSID, BSSID, or nickname.

    <b>-n INDEX|ESSID|BSSID|NICK</b> [NICKNAME] - Set Nickname
      Set a nickname on a saved credential. Omit nickname or
      pass <b>-</b> to clear. Nicknames can be used with <b>-u</b>.
      Shortcut for <b>-e … nick …</b>.

    <b>-e</b> / <b>edit</b> - Edit Credentials
      No args: open <b>wifi_creds</b> in vi.
      One arg: show all fields for that entry.
      Two+ args: set a field.
      Fields: <b>nick</b>, <b>pass</b>, <b>flag</b> (clean|burned),
      <b>signal</b>, <b>essid</b>, <b>burn</b> (mark bad), <b>delete</b> (remove).

    <b>burn</b> [INDEX|ESSID|BSSID|NICK] - Burn Network
      Mark a network as burned (bad). Stays in <b>wifi_creds</b>
      but hopping skips it. No arg burns the current AP.
      Same as <b>hop burn</b>. Use <b>-e … delete</b> to remove.

    <b>-k INDEX</b> [ACKS] - Crack Network
      Capture using ACK count from signal strength; on
      failure, rescans signal and retries once. Optional
      ACKS overrides the target (no auto-retry when ACKS
      is given).

    <b>crackall</b> [--all] - Crack Visible Networks
      Crack visible APs at <b>40%+</b> signal and write
      results to <b>wifi_creds</b>. Skips weaker APs and
      networks already saved (refreshes their signal).
      Use <b>--all</b> (or <b>-a</b>) to include weak APs.
      Does <b>not</b> start hopping. Each AP is captured once
      from signal strength; on failure, rescans signal and
      retries once. Press <b>q</b> between networks to quit
      early. Each successful crack is written to
      <b>wifi_creds</b> immediately (survives Ctrl+C).
      (q cannot interrupt mid-aireplay.) Alias: <b>hop init</b>

    <b>creds</b> - View Saved Credentials
      Show all entries in <b>wifi_creds</b> with index,
      status, nick, signal, BSSID, ESSID, and password.

    <b>hop</b> - WiFi Hopping
      Start bouncing between clean WiFi networks. Burned
      networks are skipped but kept in the file. If no
      credentials file exists, runs crackall automatically.
      Use Ctrl+C to stop.

    <b>hop init</b> [--all] - Initialize Credentials
      Same as <b>crackall</b>. Does not start hopping.

    <b>hop -t SECONDS</b> - Hop with Interval
      Start hopping with custom interval between network
      switches. Default is 3 seconds.

    <b>hop list</b> - List Arsenal
      Show saved networks with clean/burned status
      (passwords hidden). Use <b>creds</b> to see passwords.

    <b>hop burn</b> [ESSID|INDEX|NICK] - Burn Network
      Mark that network burned (bad). Kept in wifi_creds,
      skipped by hop. No arg burns current connection.

    <b>hop revive</b> <ESSID|INDEX|NICK|all> - Revive Network
      Clear burned flag so the network is usable for hop
      again. Use <b>all</b> to revive every burned entry.
<b>EXAMPLE:</b>
    <color=#e4ff34># List Networks</color>
    <b>iwlist -l</b>
    Show all WiFi networks in range

    <color=#e4ff34># Crack All + Use Saved</color>
    <b>iwlist crackall</b>
    Crack 40%+ networks into wifi_creds
    <b>iwlist crackall --all</b>
    Crack every visible network (including weak)
    <b>iwlist creds</b>
    View saved credentials (nick, signal, passwords)
    <b>iwlist -n 0 homebase</b>
    Nickname the first entry
    <b>iwlist -e 0</b>
    Show all fields for entry 0
    <b>iwlist -e 0 pass secret123</b>
    Update saved password
    <b>iwlist -e 0 burn</b>
    Mark entry burned (bad) — stays in list
    <b>iwlist burn 0</b>
    Same — mark burned by index
    <b>iwlist -e 0 delete</b>
    Actually remove entry from wifi_creds
    <b>iwlist -e</b>
    Open wifi_creds in vi
    <b>iwlist -u homebase</b>
    Connect by nickname
    <b>iwlist -u 0</b>
    Connect using first saved entry
    <b>iwlist -u HomeNetwork</b>
    Connect by ESSID from wifi_creds

    <color=#e4ff34># Dictionary Attack</color>
    <b>iwlist -d 0</b>
    Dictionary attack on first network

    <b>iwlist -d 2</b>
    Dictionary attack on third network

    <color=#e4ff34># Brute Force Attack</color>
    <b>iwlist -b 0</b>
    Brute force attack on first network

    <b>iwlist -b 1</b>
    Brute force attack on second network

    <color=#e4ff34># Connect to Network</color>
    <b>iwlist -c 00:11:22:33:44:55 HomeNetwork password123</b>
    Connect with full credentials

    <b>iwlist -c AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF GuestWiFi guest123</b>
    Connect to guest network

    <color=#e4ff34># Crack Network</color>
    <b>iwlist -k 0</b>
    Crack first network

    <b>iwlist -k 1 5000</b>
    Crack second network with 5000 ACKS

    <color=#e4ff34># Combined Workflow</color>
    <b>iwlist -l</b>
    List networks first
    <b>iwlist -d 0</b>
    Then launch dictionary attack

    <color=#e4ff34># WiFi Hopping</color>
    <b>iwlist crackall</b>
    Crack 40%+ networks and save credentials

    <b>iwlist hop</b>
    Start hopping (auto-crackall if no creds)

    <b>iwlist hop -t 5</b>
    Hop with 5 second interval

    <b>iwlist hop list</b>
    Show arsenal status (no passwords)

    <b>iwlist hop burn</b>
    Mark current connected network burned (bad)

    <b>iwlist burn Yco</b>
    Mark network burned by ESSID

    <b>iwlist hop burn 2</b>
    Mark network burned by index

    <b>iwlist hop revive Yco</b>
    Un-burn a specific network

    <b>iwlist hop revive all</b>
    Revive all burned networks
<b>SEE ALSO</b>
    <b>hunt</b>, <b>scan</b>"
